:formula_34

Here, the right hand side is clearly not convergent for any non-zero value of &quot;t&quot;. However, by truncating the series on the right to a finite number of terms, one may obtain a fairly good approximation to the value of formula_35 for sufficiently small &quot;t&quot;. Substituting formula_36 and noting that formula_37 results in the asymptotic expansion given earlier in this article.

=== Integration by parts ===
Using integration by parts, we can obtain an explicit formulaformula_38For any fixed formula_39, the absolute value of the error term formula_40 decreases, then increases. The minimum occurs at formula_41, at which point formula_42. This bound is said to be &quot;asymptotics beyond all orders&quot;.

==Properties==
===Uniqueness for a given asymptotic scale===
For a given asymptotic scale formula_43 the asymptotic expansion of function formula_44 is unique. That is the coefficients formula_45 are uniquely determined in the following way:
formula_46
where formula_47 is the limit point of this asymptotic expansion (may be formula_48).

===Non-uniqueness for a given function===
A given function formula_44 may have many asymptotic expansions (each with a different asymptotic scale).

===Subdominance===
An asymptotic expansion may be an asymptotic expansion to more than one function.

