<doc id="642101" wikidata="Q207726" url="?curid=642101" title="Cardioid">
<text>In geometry, a cardioid () is a plane curve traced by a point on the perimeter of a circle that is rolling around a fixed circle of the same radius. It can also be defined as an epicycloid having a single cusp. It is also a type of sinusoidal spiral, and an inverse curve of the parabola with the focus as the center of inversion. A cardioid can also be defined as the set of points of reflections of a fixed point on a circle through all tangents to the circle.

The name was coined by Giovanni Salvemini in 1741 but the cardioid had been the subject of study decades beforehand. Although named for its heart-like form, it is shaped more like the outline of the cross-section of a round apple without the stalk.

A cardioid microphone exhibits an acoustic pickup pattern that, when graphed in two dimensions, resembles a cardioid (any 2d plane containing the 3d straight line of the microphone body). In three dimensions, the cardioid is shaped like an apple centred around the microphone which is the &quot;stalk&quot; of the apple.

== Equations ==

Let formula_1 be the common radius of the two generating circles with midpoints formula_2, formula_3 the rolling angle and the origin the starting point (see picture). One gets the
* parametric representation: formula_4 and herefrom the representation in
* polar coordinates: formula_5
* Introducing the substitutions formula_6 and formula_7 one gets after removing the square root the implicit representation in Cartesian coordinates: formula_8

===Proof for the parametric representation===
A proof can be established using complex numbers and their common description as the complex plane. The rolling movement of the black circle on the blue one can be split into two rotations. In the complex plane a rotation around point formula_9 (the origin) by an angle formula_3 can be performed by multiplying a point formula_11 (complex number) by formula_12. Hence
: the rotation formula_13 around point formula_1 isformula_15,
: the rotation formula_16 around point formula_17 is: formula_18.
A point formula_19 of the cardioid is generated by rotating the origin around point formula_1 and subsequently rotating around formula_17 by the same angle formula_3:
formula_23
From here one gets the parametric representation above:
formula_24
(The trigonometric identities formula_25 formula_26 and formula_27 were used.)

== Metric properties ==
For the cardioid as defined above the following formulas hold:
* &quot;area&quot; formula_28,
* &quot;arc length&quot; formula_29 and
* &quot;radius of curvature&quot; formula_30
The proofs of these statements use in both cases the polar representation of the cardioid. For suitable formulas see polar coordinate system (arc length) and polar coordinate system (area)

